1 incl uding, but not limited to, a district attorney or city or
2 municipal attorney; and
3 2. "Law enforcement agency" means an agency of the state or an
4 agency of a political subdivision of the state authorized by law to
5 employ peace officers.
6 B. When evaluating the credibility of a peace officer who is
7 serving or will serve as a witness in a criminal proceeding, the
8 attorney representing the state may not disqualify the peace officer
9 as a witness on the basis of an allegation of misconduct by the
10 peace officer that has not been finally adjudicated as sustained.
11 C. For purposes of this section, an allegation of misconduct by
12 a peace officer is not considered finally adjudicated as sustained
13 if the allegation is under appeal through an administrative process
14 or judicial proceeding.
15 D. A peace officer who:
16 1. Is the subject of an allegation of misconduct reported by a
17 law enforcement agency to an attorney representing the state;
18 2. Has been notified of a determination by an attorney
19 representing the state that the peace officer is not considered
20 credible to testify in a criminal proceeding as a result of an
21 allegation of misconduct; or
22 3. Has his or her name placed on a "Do Not Call" list of
23 noncredible peace officers by a law enforcement agency or an
24 attorney representing the state, may dispute the report,
