1 dete rmination, or listing by filing a petition with the Office of
2 the Attorney General for the purpose of contesting said allegation,
3 determination, listing, or other similar action that adversely
4 reflects on the credibility of the peace officer. Upon request by
5 the affected peace officer, the attorney representing the state or
6 relevant law enforcement agency shall provide the underlying facts
7 affecting the credibility of the peace officer to the peace officer
8 for purposes of a hearing under subsection E of this section.
9 E. The Office of the Attorney General shall refer the petition
10 to an administrative law judge for an evidentiary hearing. The
11 administrative law judge shall provide findings of fact and
12 conclusions of law as to the validity of the allegations of
13 misconduct by the peace officer that resulted in the peace officer
14 being placed on a "Do Not Call" list of noncredible peace officers.
15 The respondent in the hearing shall be the law enforcement agency
16 that reported or alleged the misconduct by the peace officer.
17 F. 1. If a peace officer has been placed on a "Do Not Call"
18 list of noncredible peace officers due to an allegation of
19 misconduct and the administrative process addressing said allegation
20 is still pending or has been appealed, the administrative law judge
21 shall find in favor of the peace officer.
22 2. If the administrative law judge finds the allegations of
23 misconduct are not supported by a preponderance of the evidence, the
24 law enforcement agency and attorney for the state may not rely on
